													<td>
														<p class="textNormal">The Indian BPO industry is growing at an overwhelming pace 
															giving a major boost to the Indian economy. India has established its 
															leadership position globally in the outsourcing market and now the availability 
															of skilled manpower is one of the key barriers to the fast growth of the 
															industry.
														</p>
														<p class="textNormal">NASSCOM, with the support from the Indian BPO industry 
															partners, has devised an assessment-cum-certification program - the NASSCOM 
															Assessment of Competence (NAC). The initiative is aimed at creating a robust 
															and continuous pipeline of talent that is suitable for the BPO jobs. This will 
															be done by continuously assessing candidates on key skills through NAC, thus 
															making it easier for firms to screen candidates and also provide them with 
															training-need analysis. This shall further be tied in to training and 
															development efforts by different stakeholders to help more candidates become 
															competent to work in the industry. NASSCOM eventually aims to build a pool of 
															potential candidates, which will be pre-certified (i.e. through NAC), in tune 
															with the needs of the industry and thereby gear up for the future requirements 
															of the sector.
														</p>
													</td>
												</tr>
												<tr>
													<td>&nbsp;</td>
												</tr>
												<tr>
													<td class="textNormal" style="FONT-WEIGHT: bold; FONT-SIZE: 13px; FONT-FAMILY: tahoma">
														Phase I Approach
													</td>
												</tr>
												<tr>
													<td>
														<p class="textNormal">In the year 2005, in-depth meetings with close to 35 Indian 
															BPO companies were conducted to understand their recruitment practices, cause 
															of attrition, desired skills in a candidate, etc. Based on this, a job-skill 
															matrix was developed which formed the basis for designing of the NAC 
															assessment. Committees from the industry were formed to ensure that the program 
															has everything that the industry requires in terms of a pre-employment 
															assessment. Thereafter, the ‘NAC pilot phase-I’ was kicked-off where RFQ 
															(Request For Quote) was sent to about 19 vendors and 11 of them qualified for 
															next level evaluation. After a round of detailed presentations and 
															comprehensive evaluation, 4 vendors were chosen, with whom the pilot was 
															initiated. The objective of pilot was to understand the industry 
															benchmarks/thresholds vis-à-vis the skills required by companies and also to 
															identify the worth of each of the final vendors, who could be used for the 
															‘National Rollout’ of the NAC program. These vendors provided the content and 
															technology to run the pilot. Selected companies from the industry, identified 
															by NASSCOM, partnered in deployment of the pilot program. The locations for the 
															first stage of pilot were identified as Delhi-NCR, Mumbai, Bangalore and 
															Chennai and about 6,000 assessments were conducted during the pilot.</p>
													</td>
												</tr>
												<tr>
